		<div class="post-460 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-copyleft category-copywrong category-free-culture category-money category-questioncopyrightorg category-the-interwebs" id="post-460">


<div class="post-headline">		<h2>			
			<a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/2009/04/06/understanding-free-content/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Understanding Free Content">Understanding Free Content</a></h2>
		</div>

<div class="post-bodycopy clearfix"><p><strong>Content</strong> is an <strong>unlimited resource</strong>. People can now make perfect copies of digital content for free. That&#8217;s why they expect content to be free — because it is in fact free. That is GOOD.</p>
<p>Think of &#8220;content&#8221; — culture — as water.  Where water flows, life flourishes.</p>
<p><center><img src="http://www.questioncopyright.org/cm/images/ufc/content_is_free.png" alt="content is free, like water in a river" border="0" width="433" /></center><strong>Containers</strong> — objects like books, DVDs, hard drives, apparel, action figures, and prints — are not free. They are a <strong>limited resource</strong>.  No one expects these objects to be free, and people voluntarily pay good money for them.</p>
<p><center><img src="http://www.questioncopyright.org/cm/images/ufc/containers_not_free.png" alt="containers are not free" border="0" width="433" /></center>Think of &#8220;containers&#8221; — books, discs, hard drives — as jugs and vessels. These containers add utility to and increase the value of the water. If you can get water for free in the public river, great — that doesn&#8217;t reduce the value of vessels. Quite the contrary: when rivers flow, the utility and value of water vessels increases.</p>
<p><center><img src="http://www.questioncopyright.org/cm/images/ufc/free_vs_not_free.png" alt="free vs not free; use the unlimited resource to sell the limited resource" border="0" width="433" /></center><center> </center><center><a href="http://www.questioncopyright.org/understanding_free_content" title="Read the rest of this post">Read the rest of this article…</a> </center><center> </center></p>
<div class="plus-one-wrap"><g:plusone href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/2009/04/06/understanding-free-content/"></g:plusone></div><div class="addtoany_share_save_container"><div class="a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_target addtoany_list" id="wpa2a_9"><a class="a2a_dd addtoany_share_save" href="http://www.addtoany.com/share_save" style="background:url(http://blog.ninapaley.com/wp-content/plugins/add-to-any/favicon.png) no-repeat scroll 4px 0px !important;padding:0 0 0 25px;display:inline-block;height:16px;vertical-align:middle">Share/Bookmark</a></div></div><p class="wp-flattr-button"><a class="FlattrButton" style="display:none;" href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/2009/04/06/understanding-free-content/" title=" Understanding Free Content" rev="flattr;uid:ninapaley;language:en_GB;category:text;tags:blog;button:compact;">Content is an unlimited resource. People can now make perfect copies of digital content for free. That&#8217;s why they expect content to be free — because it is in fact free. That...</a></p></div>

<div class="post-footer">April 6th, 2009 |  Category: <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/copyleft/" title="View all posts in copyleft" rel="category tag">copyleft</a>, <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/copywrong/" title="View all posts in copywrong" rel="category tag">copywrong</a>, <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/free-culture/" title="View all posts in Free Culture" rel="category tag">Free Culture</a>, <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/money/" title="View all posts in money" rel="category tag">money</a>, <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/questioncopyrightorg/" title="View all posts in questioncopyright.org" rel="category tag">questioncopyright.org</a>, <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/category/the-interwebs/" title="View all posts in the interwebs" rel="category tag">the interwebs</a> | <a href="http://blog.ninapaley.com/2009/04/06/understanding-free-content/#comments" class="comments-link"  title="Comment on Understanding Free Content">2 comments</a> </div>
</div><!-- / Post -->						
		
		 

